Gene Expression Fundamentals using DESeq

Devika Godbole

11/19/2020

In this project, we are primarily interested in understanding how the differences in gene expression between the light and dark conditions vary by genotype. To this end, we will use DESeq to look for genes with significant interaction terms between genotype and timepoint.

To begin, we construct a DESeqDataSet object using time + genotype + time:genotype as the design argument and perform a hypothesis test specifically for the significance of the interaction term time:genotype in the model.

## [1] 1429
## [1] 142.9

If we wanted to keep the false discovery rate (FDR) to 0.10 (or 10%), we would conclude that there was evidence of a significant time:genotype interaction term for 1429 genes from the full data set.

The expected number of false positive discoveries out of the list of genes with evidence of significant interaction terms determined this way would be 142.9 because 1429 samples that were below the cutoff adjusted p value and we expect 10% of those to be false discoveries.

Next, the data was normalized with DESeq and log-transformed with an offset and the dimensions of lgNorm are outputted.

## [1] 18399    15

From the PCA plot, it still appears that the the DAY samples versus the DARK samples are the most separated from each other along the PC1 direction. Along the PC2 direction, there is not a very clear separation between any of the genotypes. The 14B DARK and 14B DAY groups have much more variation/less clustering in this sample compared to the full data set. The 14B group as a whole does not fit any pattern when compared to the 4G group and the Col group.

Next, we generate a clustered heatmap of the differences in each gene’s (log-transformed normalized) expression level from it’s (the gene’s, that is) mean.

From the sample-axis dendrogram, we can see thee are two major groups- one with the samples from DAY and another with samples from DARK. The gene expression patterns between these two groups are inversely related upon visual inspection of the heatmap. From the gene-axis dendrogram, we can see that there is a division between the gene group {KIN1, COR15B, COR15A} and the rest of the genes in the gene ontology. The gene group of interest have much higher differences in expression values from the means of each gene. The gene CFB2, XERO1, TCF1, DRES1A, and AZI1, not a part of our gene group of interest, also appear to have strong deviation from the mean gene expression levels.

Finally, we create a stripchart showing the expression levels of these genes by time and genotype (using the function provided).

The expression of these genes clearly vary by DAY/DARK status. Since we can pretty clearly see groupings of up vs down arrows for most of the genotypes across all 9 genes. There is also a slightly less clear pattern of gene expression varying across genotype. For genes the expression of the 4G and Col genotypes is similar and the expression of the 14B genotype is more distinct from them for all except genes AT1G32440 and AT1G50460. For genotypes Col, expression is higher in DAY and lower during DARK for 6/9 genes. For genotype 14B however, expression is higher in DARK and lower in DAY for 6/9 genes. For genotype 4G, there expression is not discernibly higher for either DARK or DAY among the 9 genes.
